with three colons to start, three colons to end, and then your class of dot panel dash tab set,

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:45.359
you'll define specific tabs by level two headers. So, you know, two pound signs, element one,

00:20:45.359 --> 00:20:49.760
that'll be your first tab, two pound signs, element two, that'll be your second tab. And

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:55.839
then you can have content within each of them. What this looks like in practice is you might

00:20:55.839 --> 00:21:02.239
actually have code and output. So, if I were to click on code first, it'll just show off the code

00:21:02.239 --> 00:21:08.400
that is unevaluated. But if Rachel were to click on output, it would actually show the output there

00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:13.040
on her screen. So, now she can actually click through and see, you know, have some type of

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:18.160
interactivity or have some type of interaction with the document in addition to me actually

00:21:18.160 --> 00:21:23.920
having to step through all of it. Again, this is limited to HTML output because there's that true

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:31.280
interactivity, but just showing that these fence divs are not just for kind of doing some of the

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:35.520
basics but allow you to do more across all the different HTML formats as well.

00:21:38.079 --> 00:21:44.479
If I wanted to create or show how that was actually shown on the page, that dot panel tab set,

00:21:44.479 --> 00:21:50.160
and then I have a level two header code. I have some, you know, R code that I'm putting in there.

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:56.160
I have another level two header called output. And that one is actually going to eval equals true,

00:21:56.160 --> 00:22:03.040
basically show the output, but echo equals false and not show the source code itself.

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:07.760
This is just a basic example, but you can imagine that you could have, again,

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:13.439
these multiple tab sets that you're using with fence divs, allowing the user to explore your

00:22:13.439 --> 00:22:18.319
document and interact more with it as they're reading through or walking through the document.

00:22:21.359 --> 00:22:25.839
The other item that allows you to, again, either protect yourself against different formats you're

00:22:25.839 --> 00:22:31.680
creating for or just do cool things are what are called bracketed spans. We have a sentence

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:39.040
on this page that is missing some words. This is a magic text, basically text that shows up

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:45.199
after the fact when I click next on my side of the screen. We can do this, again, with what is

00:22:45.199 --> 00:22:52.000
called a bracketed span. So we do square brackets around specific text, in this case magic text for

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:58.560
the previous example we were showing. And then just like with our fence divs, we apply a specific

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:04.719
class to that text. The main difference between these two is that a fence div will apply to like

00:23:04.719 --> 00:23:11.199
an entire paragraph or a collection of text. And a bracketed span could be applied to a single word

00:23:11.199 --> 00:23:16.560
or single words within an overall sentence. So you can imagine, you know, applying to the whole

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:22.319
paragraph versus small components of that, again, to, you know, help tell your story or indicate

00:23:22.319 --> 00:23:29.520
something on the page. Here I'm using a dot fragment class, which is specific to presentations,

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:35.839
but this lets you actually delay the presentation and delay the specific word to show up later as

00:23:35.839 --> 00:23:41.599
you're moving through that slide deck. So overall, you know, bracketed spans can do a lot, but just

00:23:41.599 --> 00:23:48.640
showing one example here quickly inside the presentation format. The structure would be

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:52.719
something like this. You're going to surround specific text that you want to affect, or the

00:23:52.719 --> 00:23:58.239
specific object you want to affect, with square brackets around it. And again, you have a left and

00:23:58.239 --> 00:24:04.239
a right square bracket indicating a start and an end of what's being modified. Once that is written

00:24:04.239 --> 00:24:10.319
out, you're going to add curly brackets to indicate the start and end of the specific class. So

00:24:10.319 --> 00:24:16.239
something like curly bracket dot class or dot fragment, and then closing it off with another

00:24:16.239 --> 00:24:22.319
curly bracket so that it can be fully interpreted. Again, this just allows you to modify specific

00:24:22.319 --> 00:24:30.640
components of the text or style your document in specific ways. One example, it's a slight

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:36.640
modification of this, and one that we use in that report about Boston Terriers, is we actually create

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:43.439
inline footnotes. So something like some inline text with a kind of tilde and then the square

00:24:43.439 --> 00:24:50.319
bracket footnote or this up arrow kind of symbol. This allows us to add a footnote or kind of this

00:24:50.319 --> 00:24:56.479
like end note to a specific word. So in the document, it will show this as like a hyperlink

00:24:56.479 --> 00:25:02.079
back to the footnote or the end note, but also allow you to inject a lot of text about that

00:25:02.079 --> 00:25:06.959
overall. So it could be kind of like a citation or just an aside or a comment that you're making

00:25:06.959 --> 00:25:15.359
that you don't want to display all the time. In HTML, these can be hoverable in terms of in an

00:25:15.359 --> 00:25:20.719
HTML document, I can actually hover over those footnotes and see them displayed kind of as an

00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:26.319
overlay in the document. In a PDF, they don't necessarily have the ability to render that

00:25:26.319 --> 00:25:32.079
additional JavaScript or CSS, so they're just linked to the footnote or the end note at the

00:25:32.079 --> 00:25:38.319
end of the page or at the end of the document. And what this looks like in practice is I might have

00:25:38.319 --> 00:25:42.719
a sentence like, for example, did you know that Howard is a dog? And then adding a specific

00:25:42.719 --> 00:25:48.400
footnote, specifically he is a Boston Terrier, although sometimes he acts like a cat. So by

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:54.079
providing that footnote, you know, that specifically all the way through cat, that whole section is

00:25:54.079 --> 00:25:59.359
hidden on the page, but added as this footnote providing an additional context about the sentence

00:25:59.359 --> 00:26:04.560
as we're walking through it. So if you're using this for kind of scientific documentation or just

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:14.079
kind of asides you're making a useful thing to add to your documents. The unified syntax can also do

00:26:14.079 --> 00:26:19.760
more complex things in terms of we move back to fence divs, we can overall structure our document.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:26.640
So here from that actual article I showed, I have a mixing of images aligning those with text and

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:32.719
paragraphs and putting it together something like this. So for here, I've applied a layout class

00:26:32.719 --> 00:26:38.719
and I have the image as 30 percent of the width of the page, and then layout equals to 70 percent

00:26:38.719 --> 00:26:44.959
for paragraph one, and then below that 100 indicating that paragraph two will take up the

00:26:44.959 --> 00:26:51.839
remaining width of the page below the other two. And again, regardless of the output format, PDF or

00:26:51.839 --> 00:27:00.239
Word or HTML, I can structure and kind of typeset my document using this type of syntax. I can also

00:27:00.239 --> 00:27:05.359
move one of those images into the margin. So, you know, I had the small Boston Terrier that was on

00:27:05.359 --> 00:27:11.119
the right side of the screen, I have a traditional kind of hyperlink to an image on this page,

00:27:11.839 --> 00:27:20.079
and then I have a specific class on that called a dot column dash margin, and that actually takes

00:27:20.079 --> 00:27:25.199
the image and throws it into the margin of the overall document while the rest of the body

00:27:25.199 --> 00:27:32.400
continues on. And then as we talked about just previously, add things like footnotes. So information

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:38.239
about where did I get this detail, the average life of a Boston Terrier is around 11 to 13 years.

00:27:38.239 --> 00:27:43.680
This was retrieved from the Boston Terrier Club of America and providing additional context about

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:50.880
that citation or around that detail that we're adding. So this unified syntax, again, while I

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:54.959
think that writing for HTML is some of the most powerful way you can actually do this,

00:27:55.760 --> 00:28:01.119
in certain situations you have to write to PDF or you want to write to PDF or to Word doc so you can

00:28:01.119 --> 00:28:06.479
collaborate on them in a different way, you can use this unified syntax across different output

00:28:06.479 --> 00:28:15.760
formats with a Cordo report you're putting together. Again, while I think that Cordo reports,

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:20.400
you know, in terms of making them look beautiful and typesetting them is very useful, ultimately

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:26.800
a different value that Cordo provides is that it can also add code in both the display of that code,

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:32.640
the hiding of that code, or, you know, just the output of that code itself as a graphic, as a table,

00:28:32.640 --> 00:28:39.680
or as raw text. So in your document you might have something like this, where you have an HTML

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:45.760
document you're creating and you want to have, you know, the code not be shown. Maybe you're

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:51.040
generating a report that's going up to leadership, they don't necessarily want to read R code or

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:55.680
Python code, they just want to see the final report. They don't necessarily care how you got there,

00:28:56.319 --> 00:29:01.599
maybe they just want to see the details. So in this case you can still keep the source code,

00:29:01.599 --> 00:29:06.880
so you can keep your .qmd that has all the source code, the links out to the data,

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:12.160
basically how you got there, but when you generate out your report it doesn't show any of the code,

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:18.880
it just shows the output and the commentary that you've added to it. You can still turn on code

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:24.640
individually, so let's say you turned on echo equals false at the top in the YAML. At the code

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:30.239
chunk level you can actually add and say like for this one code chunk I want it to be echo equals

00:29:30.239 --> 00:29:35.839
true. So regardless of what the YAML says, turn echo and actually show the code for this specific

00:29:35.839 --> 00:29:42.319
document. You can also, rather than hide all the code and make it where no one can see it,

00:29:42.319 --> 00:29:49.040
is you can do what's called code folding. And in this case you'll have code folding that you can

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:55.040
hide temporarily in terms of it'll fold all the code behind a little menu bar that you can click

00:29:55.040 --> 00:30:00.560
on and that little menu bar will be called hidden code. So you can click on each individual code

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:07.920
chunk and display it and then collapse it as you move forward. And again this could be turned on

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:13.199
at the specific code chunk level where I could have code folding turned on for one code chunk,

00:30:13.199 --> 00:30:17.760
so even if I was hiding all the rest of it for one that might be really important,

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:23.040
I can still say hey this one allows you to toggle the code showing on or off again.

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:31.680
Going a bit further, you know, maybe we want to show the code, maybe you don't want to show the

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:37.599
code, we can also use what are called code dash tools. So in your format, might have format equals

00:30:37.599 --> 00:30:45.280
html or pdf, code tools equals true gives us this little overlay where the user can make all of the

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:50.640
decisions. So at the very top of the document they can have this little drop down and they can you

00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:56.400
know hide all the code or show all the code or in some situations even view the source document.

00:30:56.400 --> 00:31:01.040
So you can embed all of the source code into the document and when you click on it that allows you

00:31:01.040 --> 00:31:08.640
to show all the source code before the results were generated or link out to an external repository.

00:31:09.599 --> 00:31:14.079
Again this just allows you to make those decisions as you're using it for reporting

00:31:14.079 --> 00:31:19.040
but you can choose how much of the code or how much of the context you want to display for your users.

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:27.280
If we wanted to show the source in terms of like literally embed the source code into the document

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:33.920
you could use code tools equals source equals true, toggle equals false, and no caption.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:39.199
And this will allow you to see the source code but all the code is also displayed in the

00:31:39.199 --> 00:31:44.479
document and you're not trying to hide it, you're just trying to also embed all that source code so

00:31:44.479 --> 00:31:49.359
that users can see it or you as you're automating that report can also see

00:31:49.359 --> 00:31:53.439
how the document was generated and if anything has changed over time.

00:31:56.239 --> 00:32:00.239
Overall when you display or look at the source code it might look something like this

00:32:00.239 --> 00:32:05.680
where you have an overlay that pops up displaying what was all the source code that you used,

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:09.920
literally the markdown as well as the code chunks and all the options of it.

00:32:09.920 --> 00:32:13.520
So again very useful for kind of checking that your source code

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:15.920
is actually valid for what your expectations are.

00:32:18.959 --> 00:32:23.199
For other situations where you don't necessarily want to embed all the source code into the

00:32:23.199 --> 00:32:27.760
document or in some situation where you really don't want to show the code itself you want to

00:32:27.760 --> 00:32:32.800
have it in like a private github repository or maybe it's just really long and you don't want

00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:38.959
to embed all of that because the user experience is not ideal, you could actually use code tools

00:32:38.959 --> 00:32:46.079
plus source and indicate an external repository. So here we're linking out to cordo-dev and

00:32:46.079 --> 00:32:52.400
linking out to a specific markdown file that displays the source code for that specific page.

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:56.959
So they can actually go and look at it on a first class you know version control system

00:32:56.959 --> 00:33:02.239
as opposed to embedding it into the document itself. But again you get to make that decision

00:33:02.239 --> 00:33:06.479
in terms of displaying the code, hiding the code, embedding the source code,

00:33:06.479 --> 00:33:09.760
all those different things you can do for your user's experience.

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:17.520
We can then move on to things like making the overall document look a bit better.

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:23.359
So maybe you do want to show the code but you have like a dark theme or you have a specific

00:33:23.359 --> 00:33:29.199
style that you want to apply to the code. So by default your code might look something like this

00:33:29.199 --> 00:33:34.880
where it's highlighting things like library dplyr and your groupby and other function calls are

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:41.599
highlighted in blue your arguments are in green and it's doing some highlighting of specific

00:33:41.599 --> 00:33:47.280
components but it's really white on white with this background. There's a lot of highlighting

00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:53.599
options that I've included in a link at the full highlighting options but you can modify this

00:33:53.599 --> 00:33:59.839
throughout your document. So for our different themes let's say we're using an html report

00:33:59.839 --> 00:34:05.040
we can stick with highlight style equals arrow which will look something like this where you have

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:10.639
blue for function calls you can have logical statements that are a little bit lighter blue

00:34:10.639 --> 00:34:15.840
numerics are in red and it allows you to kind of read the source code a bit easier as opposed to

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:23.679
them all being one color all being black or gray or something. But again what if you made this into

00:34:23.679 --> 00:34:30.479
like a dark mode? So here we've modified the yaml header to have the same highlight style of arrow

00:34:30.479 --> 00:34:35.120
which is the one we're trying to use for accessibility reasons for contrast and other

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:42.639
things but then we had the ability to toggle on and off a light mode and a dark mode. So in Cordo

00:34:42.639 --> 00:34:48.479
if you use a theme equals light and theme equals dark and change those out you can actually have a

00:34:48.479 --> 00:34:55.040
toggleable option to make a switch from light mode into dark mode. Now this again will modify

00:34:55.040 --> 00:35:02.000
how the code itself looks on the page because your background is black. So you can use a highlight

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:07.520
style like arrow that works for both light and dark and it will actually modify the background

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:13.679
color of the source code to also match the light or the dark theme. So again by changing out some

00:35:13.679 --> 00:35:18.719
of the styling you can make your overall document look the same or have the same kind of theming or

00:35:18.719 --> 00:35:27.280
consistency as you move across it. So while you know changing code itself is kind of cool overall

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:31.679
you're probably a bit more interested in what you know what else you can do with that code.

00:35:32.800 --> 00:35:39.120
So in R there's a package called download and this not only provides like syntax highlighting

00:35:39.120 --> 00:35:45.760
but also links out to specific source code. So if you're using download and actually evaluating code

00:35:45.760 --> 00:35:52.320
this will actually allow you to click on the functions in the chunk output and it'll actually

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:57.280
link out to the documentation for that. So you imagine someone's like oh I saw this cool package

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:02.320
called per and it's got this function called walk that Tom was talking about in the presentation.

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:08.159
You can actually click on my source code and click on per walk and it will take you to the

00:36:08.159 --> 00:36:14.479
documentation for per walk. So you can read a bit more about that function. So download again will

00:36:14.479 --> 00:36:20.080
provide this linking of the R code to external documentation so that when people find something

00:36:20.080 --> 00:36:24.800
they've never used before they can actually move forward into the documentation and have a lot of

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:33.199
power there to learn on the fly. So while code is cool ultimately I think that you want to do

00:36:33.199 --> 00:36:38.800
something like the overall aesthetics. You have Howard here and his you know finest garb he wants

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:44.000
to look good for the presentation. You also want your report or your presentation to look nice for

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:52.239
your users or for your kind of stakeholders. So for HTML documents out of the box Cordo is

00:36:52.239 --> 00:36:58.080
styled with something called Bootstrap 5. This is the CSS framework for websites and version 5

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:04.000
is one of the latest versions. It overall applies a lot of different theming to the overall document.

00:37:05.199 --> 00:37:10.239
So Cordo comes pre-installed with 25 different themes allowing you to set the aesthetics or the

00:37:10.239 --> 00:37:16.399
appearance of the overall document and you can use them in one or two lines of code. So in your YAML

00:37:16.399 --> 00:37:23.439
header you might define a format equals HTML and the theme as something like litera. That is a nice

00:37:23.439 --> 00:37:30.479
minimal theme that really makes the information pop as opposed to trying to make a really fancy

00:37:30.479 --> 00:37:35.679
background or something. But there's lots of different themes that you can customize and go

00:37:35.679 --> 00:37:42.800
further. Maybe you want to start from the litera theme but further customize it with a .scss file

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:48.399
that's modifying the structure or the appearance of the document beyond the defaults that are

00:37:48.399 --> 00:37:53.600
applied with the litera theme. So you're not stuck with it you can continue to customize it

00:37:53.600 --> 00:37:58.959
with either CSS files or SCSS files in this case if you're using the theme output.

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:06.959
Bootstrap themes are, you know, there's many of them. Again I mentioned 25. I just have a small

00:38:06.959 --> 00:38:12.320
selection of six here on the page. So again these are going to change all the different elements

00:38:12.320 --> 00:38:20.479
typefaces, menu bars, nav bars, the overall kind of weight of different fonts, and then colors of

00:38:20.479 --> 00:38:26.080
both the background, the foreground, and buttons. So when you're creating these HTML documents this

00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:31.919
again allows you to create nice looking documents and not having to change all the specific

00:38:31.919 --> 00:38:36.560
components yourself but using these pre-built themes that look really nice out of the box.

00:38:36.560 --> 00:38:46.959
When I gave some initial overview talk about kind of reporting or in our first workshop we did

00:38:46.959 --> 00:38:52.000
there's a lot of people asking about PDFs. You know obviously I think HTML is one of the best

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:57.520
formats and you can do the most with it but in certain situations like a journal article they

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:04.320
want to get a LaTeX file or they want to get a PDF or in some organizations just they want PDFs

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:09.840
because they're emailing them around or doing things like that. So Cordo can accept what are

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:16.080
called templates that allow you to style or kind of take it as a default structure with LaTeX files.

00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:22.479
So if you have those laying around or modify them you can further customize and optimize for PDF

00:39:22.479 --> 00:39:30.320
if that's the route you want to go. There's also support for kind of first class journal

00:39:30.320 --> 00:39:37.120
articles from Cordo so actually taking a document not having to go and do write all this LaTeX code

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:42.479
that you're customizing it with but just using one of the Cordo journal formats and publishing

00:39:42.479 --> 00:39:49.919
it out to a specific kind of specific publication that you want to go to like the ACM or the Journal

00:39:49.919 --> 00:39:55.280
of Statistical Science or something like that and you can end up with a report that looks really

00:39:55.280 --> 00:40:01.040
really nice with this journal statistical software where again you're not having to write

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:07.679
all of the custom LaTeX to make the PDF look like this but rather making use of Cordo's built-in

00:40:08.639 --> 00:40:13.840
kind of Cordo journals formats that are available and just writing things like what is the abstract

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:19.679
what is the title what are the authors and their affiliations and it will take that and build it

00:40:19.679 --> 00:40:25.280
into the document to actually provide a useful output or what the journal statistical software

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:31.280
is expecting when you actually deliver the article to them. Again Cordo wants to support this idea of

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:35.760
reproducible science you know whether that's science in an organization and you're creating

