01:09:53.600 --> 01:10:01.200
maybe has hundreds of R Markdown reports? Yeah, I would say overall, the beauty is that we support

01:10:01.200 --> 01:10:06.560
both in terms of if I say we as in our studio, like the core team that works on R Markdown is

01:10:06.560 --> 01:10:12.240
the same team that works on Cordo. So you don't have to change everything, which is a great thing.

01:10:12.240 --> 01:10:16.000
Like if someone told you tomorrow, hey, stop doing what you're doing and move to this,

01:10:16.720 --> 01:10:22.080
that would be very disruptive, and that's not the goal of anything with Cordo. There are

01:10:22.080 --> 01:10:26.720
differences, and there are trade-offs and benefits for using Cordo or using R Markdown for certain

01:10:26.720 --> 01:10:31.759
situations. But especially if you've got like a thousand line R Markdown report, or you've got a

01:10:31.759 --> 01:10:37.120
workflow that's working, great, like keep using it. Like we're continuing to support R Markdown.

01:10:37.120 --> 01:10:42.240
We're not like abandoning it. We are still doing bug fixes and kind of improvements over time.

01:10:42.799 --> 01:10:48.879
Just if you think about it with like new features, there were limitations in terms of how we extended

01:10:48.879 --> 01:10:54.720
R Markdown. The way to extend R Markdown was to write another R package that extended it,

01:10:54.720 --> 01:11:00.799
and with Cordo, a lot of it is baked into the one install. So rather than having to manage

01:11:00.799 --> 01:11:08.000
multiple packages or have it be only with R, we're trying to not only improve things for our R users,

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:13.759
but also bring essentially like all of R Markdown to the Julia language and to Python and to teams

01:11:13.759 --> 01:11:20.399
that don't even use code. Like just bring a visual editor and Markdown-style scientific

01:11:20.399 --> 01:11:27.439
communication without having to manage data science languages. So it's a bit hard of a

01:11:27.439 --> 01:11:32.640
question to answer in a short format, but I would say just like if you have existing R Markdown,

01:11:32.640 --> 01:11:37.759
you can keep using them. For basic R Markdown, you can use Cordo to actually

01:11:37.759 --> 01:11:41.600
render or convert those, but you definitely don't have to convert over.

